Two-jump simulations

Binseginf

Oct 13th, 2016

  • Objective
  • Simulation
  • QQ-plots of p-values

Objective

  • From one-jump generated data, compare the conditional power of two types of tests from two-step binary segmentation models.
    • Observe 1st jump correctly, test that first jump.
    • Observe 1st & 2nd jump correctly, test the first jump.

Simulation

Generate data from: \[ n = 12 \] \[ y \in \mathbb{R}^n \] \[ \theta = (\underbrace{0,\cdots,0}_{n/3},\underbrace{\delta,\cdots,\delta}_{n/3},\underbrace{0,\cdots,0}_{n/3}) \in \mathbb{R}^n \] We will consider single signal size \(\delta = 3\).

QQ-plots of p-values

  • Simulation results
    • One-step models: There are 1817 out of 5000 simulations whose one-step model that hit \(n/3=\) 4.
    • Two-step models: There are 1467 out of 5000 simulations whose two-step model hit \(n/3=\) 4 and \(2n/3=\) 8.
